That's a very common and effective setup! Since you are using Next.js to serve **static pages**, the usage pattern is exactly the same as the standard React example, but you benefit from Next.js's routing and build process.

The key thing to remember is that **UI components like `CodeSampleBlock` (which rely on browser APIs like `ClipboardJS`) must be rendered on the client-side.**

Here is a complete guide on how to structure and use it within a Next.js project.

### 1. Project Setup (Assumptions)

I assume you have a Next.js project initialized. You will need to install the dependencies:

```bash
npm install react react-dom clipboard-js
# If you are using TypeScript, ensure your types are installed
npm install --save-dev @types/clipboard-js
```

### 2. The Component (`components/CodeSampleBlock.tsx`)

Keep the component code exactly as we finalized it in TypeScript.

```tsx
// components/CodeSampleBlock.tsx
import React, { useState, useEffect } from 'react';
// NOTE: We import ClipboardJS here. 
// For Next.js/SSR, we must ensure this code only runs on the client.
import ClipboardJS from 'clipboard'; 

type CodeSampleBlockProps = {
  title: string;
  language: string;
  code: string;
};

const CodeSampleBlock: React.FC<CodeSampleBlockProps> = ({ title, language, code }) => {
  const [copied, setCopied] = useState(false);

  // useEffect runs only on the client side after mounting
  useEffect(() => {
    // Check if the ClipboardJS library is available globally (it should be if imported)
    if (typeof window !== 'undefined') {
        const clipboard = new ClipboardJS('.copy-btn');

        clipboard.on('success', () => {
          setCopied(true);
          setTimeout(() => {
            setCopied(false);
          }, 2000);
        });

        return () => {
          clipboard.destroy();
        };
    }
  }, []); // Empty dependency array means this runs once on mount

  return (
    <div className="code-sample-block">
      <div className="header">
        <div className="title">{title}</div>
        <div className="language">{language}</div>
        {/* The data-clipboard-text attribute is crucial for ClipboardJS */}
        <button 
            className="copy-btn" 
            data-clipboard-text={code}
        >
          {copied ? 'Copied!' : 'Copy'}
        </button>
      </div>
      <div className="body">
        {/* Code Line Counter */}
        <div className="code-lines">
          {code.split('\n').map((line, index) => (
            <div key={index} className="line-number">{index + 1}</div>
          ))}
        </div>
        {/* Code Display */}
        <pre className={`code language-${language}`}>
          <code>{code}</code>
        </pre>
      </div>
    </div>
  );
};

export default CodeSampleBlock;
```

### 💡 Important Consideration for Next.js (SSR Safety)

Because `ClipboardJS` relies on the browser's `window` object, running this component during the **Server-Side Rendering (SSR)** phase (when Next.js builds the initial HTML) will cause errors.

**The fix implemented above is:**
1.  Wrapping the `ClipboardJS` initialization inside a `useEffect` hook. `useEffect` only runs *after* the component has been rendered in the browser, making it safe for Next.js.
2.  Adding an explicit check (`if (typeof window !== 'undefined')`) inside the `useEffect` to be extra safe.

### 3. Usage Example (In a Page File)

You can now import and use this component directly in any of your static page files (e.g., `pages/api-docs.tsx`):

```tsx
// pages/api-docs.tsx
import React from 'react';
import CodeSampleBlock from '../components/CodeSampleBlock';

const ApiDocsPage: React.FC = () => {
  // --- Example 1: CURL Request ---
  const curlRequest = `curl -X POST 'https://api.myapp.com/v1/users' \\
  -H 'Content-Type: application/json' \\
  -d '{ "username": "testuser", "email": "test@example.com" }'`;

  // --- Example 2: Node.js Request ---
  const nodeJsRequest = `const axios = require('axios');

async function createUser() {
  try {
    const response = await axios.post('https://api.myapp.com/v1/users', {
      username: 'testuser',
      email: 'test@example.com'
    });
    console.log('User created:', response.data);
  } catch (error) {
    console.error('Error creating user:', error.message);
  }
}

createUser();`;

  return (
    <div style={{ padding: '40px', maxWidth: '900px', margin: '0 auto' }}>
      <h1>API Endpoint Documentation</h1>

      <h2>Create New User (cURL Example)</h2>
      <CodeSampleBlock 
        title="Create User Endpoint" 
        language="curl" 
        code={curlRequest} 
      />

      <hr style={{ margin: '50px 0' }} />

      <h2>Create New User (Node.js Example)</h2>
      <CodeSampleBlock 
        title="Create User Endpoint" 
        language="node.js" 
        code={nodeJsRequest} 
      />
    </div>
  );
};

export default ApiDocsPage;
```

### Summary

By using this setup:
1.  **Next.js** handles the routing and static file serving.
2.  **React** renders the components in the browser.
3.  **`useEffect`** safely initializes the browser-dependent `ClipboardJS` functionality only after the page has loaded in the user's browser.
